[The outbreak described above, in a region hitherto not found
ASF-infected which is situated in the centre of European Russia, has
been officially reported to the OIE on 22 Feb 2011 (follow-up report
no 51). The affected village is Chernoye, near Dzershinsk in the
Nizhegorod region, where 6 out of 20 susceptible pigs were found
infected. The report includes data on 5 additional outbreaks, all in
already infected southern Russian territories where the disease had
already been present, one in domestic pigs and 4 in wild boars; see,
with an interactive map, at
<http://web.oie.int/wahis/public.php?page=single_report&pop=1&reportid=10279>.

Since the start of the ASF epizootic in Russia, reportedly on 11 Sep
2009 when it spread from Georgia, 124 outbreaks have been reported; an
interactive map showing all accumulated outbreaks is available at
<http://web.oie.int/wahis/public.php?page=event_summary&reportid=8462>.

This seems the appropriate opportunity to congratulate the OIE for its
new web interface, from where the ASF reports and maps above have been
derived. Browsing is now more user-friendly. The website includes 9
main headings: Home, About us, Our scientific expertise, Support to
OIE members, Animal health in the world, International standard
Setting, Animal welfare, Food safety, publications and documentation.
The publications and documents database includes more than 5000
classified documents available in digital form, some of them dating
back to the 1st half of the 20th century. Media resources, latest
alerts, and additional information pertaining to the international
arena as well as to each of the 176 OIE member countries, are updated
and readily available. For the said and more, subscribers are
encouraged to take a look at <http://www.oie.int/>. - Mod.AS]
